(20, 1, '2020-06-21 03:02:10', '2020-06-21 03:02:10', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/starters/\">Starters</a>&nbsp;are boilerplate Gatsby sites maintained officially, or by the community.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"using-a-starter\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/working-with-starters/#using-a-starter\"></a>Using a starter</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"prerequisites\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/working-with-starters/#prerequisites\"></a>Prerequisites</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>The&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/gatsby-cli\">Gatsby CLI</a>&nbsp;installed</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"directions\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/working-with-starters/#directions\"></a>Directions</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Find the starter you’d like to use. (<em>The&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/starters/?v=2\">Starter Library</a>&nbsp;is a good place to look!</em>)</li><li>Generate a new site based on the starter. In the terminal, run:</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">Copycopy code to clipboard<code>gatsby new {your-project-name} {link-to-starter}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p><em>Don’t run the above command as-is — remember to replace {your-project-name} and {link-to-starter}!</em></p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Run your new site:</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">Copycopy code to clipboard<code>cd {your-project-name}gatsby develop</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"additional-resources\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/working-with-starters/#additional-resources\"></a>Additional resources</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Follow a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/starters/\">more detailed guide</a>&nbsp;on using Gatsby starters.</li><li>Learn how to use the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/gatsby-cli\">Gatsby CLI</a>&nbsp;tool to use starters in&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/tutorial/part-one/#using-gatsby-starters\">tutorial part one</a></li><li>Browse the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/starters/?v=2\">Starter Library</a></li><li>Check out Gatsby’s&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/gatsbyjs/gatsby-starter-default\">official default starter</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/gatsbyjs/gatsby/blob/master/docs/docs/recipes/working-with-starters.md\">Edit this page on GitHub</a>Last updated:&nbsp;June 19, 2020<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/working-with-plugins/\">PreviousWorking with Plugins</a><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/working-with-themes/\">NextWorking with Themes</a>Was this doc helpful to you?<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Recipes: Working with Starters', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '19-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-06-21 03:02:10', '2020-06-21 03:02:10', '', 19, 'http://localhost/auteros.document.com/2020/06/21/19-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(21, 1, '2020-06-21 03:02:36', '2020-06-21 03:02:36', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Data sourcing in Gatsby is plugin-driven; Source plugins fetch data from their source (e.g. the&nbsp;<code>gatsby-source-filesystem</code>&nbsp;plugin fetches data from the file system, the&nbsp;<code>gatsby-source-wordpress</code>&nbsp;plugin fetches data from the WordPress API, etc). You can also source the data yourself.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"adding-data-to-graphql\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/sourcing-data/#adding-data-to-graphql\"></a>Adding data to GraphQL</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gatsby’s&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/graphql-concepts/\">GraphQL data layer</a>&nbsp;uses nodes to model chunks of data. Gatsby source plugins add source nodes that you can query for, but you can also create source nodes yourself. To add custom data to the GraphQL data layer yourself, Gatsby provides methods you can leverage.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This recipe shows you how to add custom data using&nbsp;<code>createNode()</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"directions\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/sourcing-data/#directions\"></a>Directions</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>In&nbsp;<code>gatsby-node.js</code>&nbsp;use&nbsp;<code>sourceNodes()</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code>actions.createNode()</code>&nbsp;to create and export nodes to be able to query the data.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>gatsby-node.js</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">Copygatsby-node.js: copy code to clipboard<code>exports.sourceNodes = ({ actions, createNodeId, createContentDigest }) =&gt; {  const pokemons = [    { name: \"Pikachu\", type: \"electric\" },    { name: \"Squirtle\", type: \"water\" },  ]  pokemons.forEach(pokemon =&gt; {    const node = {      name: pokemon.name,      type: pokemon.type,      id: createNodeId(`Pokemon-${pokemon.name}`),      internal: {        type: \"Pokemon\",        contentDigest: createContentDigest(pokemon),      },    }    actions.createNode(node)  })}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Run&nbsp;<code>gatsby develop</code>.<em>Note: After making changes in&nbsp;<code>gatsby-node.js</code>&nbsp;you need to re-run&nbsp;<code>gatsby develop</code>&nbsp;for the changes to take effect.</em></li><li>Query the data (in GraphiQL or in your components).</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">Copycopy code to clipboard<code>query MyPokemonQuery {  allPokemon {    nodes {      name      type      id    }  }}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"additional-resources\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/sourcing-data/#additional-resources\"></a>Additional resources</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Walk through an example using the&nbsp;<code>gatsby-source-filesystem</code>&nbsp;plugin in&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/tutorial/part-five/#source-plugins\">tutorial part five</a></li><li>Search available source plugins in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/plugins/?=source\">Gatsby library</a></li><li>Understand source plugins by building one in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/tutorial/source-plugin-tutorial/\">source plugin tutorial</a></li><li>The createNode function&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/actions/#createNode\">documentation</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"sourcing-markdown-data-for-blog-posts-and-pages-with-graphql\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/sourcing-data/#sourcing-markdown-data-for-blog-posts-and-pages-with-graphql\"></a>Sourcing Markdown data for blog posts and pages with GraphQL</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can source Markdown data and use Gatsby’s&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/actions/#createPage\"><code>createPages</code>&nbsp;API</a>&nbsp;to create pages dynamically.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This recipe shows how to create pages from Markdown files on your local filesystem using Gatsby’s GraphQL data layer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"prerequisites\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/sourcing-data/#prerequisites\"></a>Prerequisites</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->', 'Adding data to GraphQL', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'adding-data-to-graphql', '', '', '2020-06-21 03:05:42', '2020-06-21 03:05:42', '', 0, 'http://localhost/auteros.document.com/?p=21', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(22, 1, '2020-06-21 03:02:36', '2020-06-21 03:02:36', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Data sourcing in Gatsby is plugin-driven; Source plugins fetch data from their source (e.g. the&nbsp;<code>gatsby-source-filesystem</code>&nbsp;plugin fetches data from the file system, the&nbsp;<code>gatsby-source-wordpress</code>&nbsp;plugin fetches data from the WordPress API, etc). You can also source the data yourself.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"adding-data-to-graphql\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/sourcing-data/#adding-data-to-graphql\"></a>Adding data to GraphQL</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gatsby’s&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/graphql-concepts/\">GraphQL data layer</a>&nbsp;uses nodes to model chunks of data. Gatsby source plugins add source nodes that you can query for, but you can also create source nodes yourself. To add custom data to the GraphQL data layer yourself, Gatsby provides methods you can leverage.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This recipe shows you how to add custom data using&nbsp;<code>createNode()</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"directions\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/sourcing-data/#directions\"></a>Directions</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>In&nbsp;<code>gatsby-node.js</code>&nbsp;use&nbsp;<code>sourceNodes()</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code>actions.createNode()</code>&nbsp;to create and export nodes to be able to query the data.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>gatsby-node.js</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">Copygatsby-node.js: copy code to clipboard<code>exports.sourceNodes = ({ actions, createNodeId, createContentDigest }) =&gt; {  const pokemons = [    { name: \"Pikachu\", type: \"electric\" },    { name: \"Squirtle\", type: \"water\" },  ]  pokemons.forEach(pokemon =&gt; {    const node = {      name: pokemon.name,      type: pokemon.type,      id: createNodeId(`Pokemon-${pokemon.name}`),      internal: {        type: \"Pokemon\",        contentDigest: createContentDigest(pokemon),      },    }    actions.createNode(node)  })}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Run&nbsp;<code>gatsby develop</code>.<em>Note: After making changes in&nbsp;<code>gatsby-node.js</code>&nbsp;you need to re-run&nbsp;<code>gatsby develop</code>&nbsp;for the changes to take effect.</em></li><li>Query the data (in GraphiQL or in your components).</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">Copycopy code to clipboard<code>query MyPokemonQuery {  allPokemon {    nodes {      name      type      id    }  }}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"additional-resources\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/sourcing-data/#additional-resources\"></a>Additional resources</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Walk through an example using the&nbsp;<code>gatsby-source-filesystem</code>&nbsp;plugin in&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/tutorial/part-five/#source-plugins\">tutorial part five</a></li><li>Search available source plugins in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/plugins/?=source\">Gatsby library</a></li><li>Understand source plugins by building one in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/tutorial/source-plugin-tutorial/\">source plugin tutorial</a></li><li>The createNode function&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/actions/#createNode\">documentation</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"sourcing-markdown-data-for-blog-posts-and-pages-with-graphql\"><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/recipes/sourcing-data/#sourcing-markdown-data-for-blog-posts-and-pages-with-graphql\"></a>Sourcing Markdown data